<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-050-054 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 483 564</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telecommunications  Oct 1991 v25 n10 p63(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Comparing alternative fast packet networking technologies, PartII: SMDS customer premises equipment. (switched multimegabit dataservice)(Data Communications)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Weissberger, Alan J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Switched multimegabit data service (SMDS) customer premisesequipment can be used as an alternative fast packet networkingtechnology and includes routers supporting one or multipleconnectionless network-layer protocols, workstations andmicrocomputers and SMDS data service units.andP;  SMDS interfaces willprobably function in the future with host computers, front-endprocessors, minisupercomputers, file servers, intelligent hubs andother equipment.andP;  There are a variety of reasons for leaving someSMDS-DS1 capabilities out of the IWU, and instead applying themdirectly to the network.andP;  Six main goals in the SMDS IWU-DSUinterface specifications include: generating an open specificationthat SMDS IWU and SMDS DSU vendors can implement for DS1 access,cutting down IWU hardware changes, providing integrated networkmanagement, concentrating on DS1 while allowing for a migrationpath to DS3, basing the interface specification on existingstandards as often as possible, and providing functions designedto please the user.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Switched Multimegabit Data ServiceLocal area networksConnectivityPacketsCustomer Premises EquipmentData Service Unit/Channel Service UnitsProtocolNetwork Management.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>